<div id="review_58549395" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/58549395" />
    <a title="Ami" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2281833-ami"><img alt="Ami" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1388773624p2/2281833.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/58549395?book_show_action=true">Jun 05, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ami" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ami" href="/user/show/2281833-ami">Ami</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2281833-ami?shelf=contemporary-fiction">contemporary-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer58549395" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer477599548004083294">This book leaves a bad taste in my mouth and a hole in my heart.<br/><br/>I have previously read the other two books in the Ya-Ya series, and upon completion I felt Vivi Walker was a damaged woman who sincerely tried to do the best she could with the hand she was dealt. &quot;Ya-Yas in Bloom,&quot; in particular, ended with a feeling of redemption for the entire Walker clan. However, after reading &quot;Little Altars Everywhere,&quot; I am disgusted beyond belief at this character. The Vivi Walker in this book is a bitter, a</span>
  <span id="freeText477599548004083294" style="display:none">This book leaves a bad taste in my mouth and a hole in my heart.<br /><br />I have previously read the other two books in the Ya-Ya series, and upon completion I felt Vivi Walker was a damaged woman who sincerely tried to do the best she could with the hand she was dealt. "Ya-Yas in Bloom," in particular, ended with a feeling of redemption for the entire Walker clan. However, after reading "Little Altars Everywhere," I am disgusted beyond belief at this character. The Vivi Walker in this book is a bitter, angry, cruel child molester who ruins the lives of her children. Forever. I am not able, for the life of me, to understand how other critics and readers can describe this book as "hilarious" or "witty" or "nostalgic."<br /><br />Overall, this book leaves me feeling conned. I fell for the Ya-Yas (Vivi especially) only to discover that at their core they are rotten. I am unable to reconcile the two images I now have for this family and that leaves me feeling angry and betrayed.<br /><br />Take my advice, read the other Ya-Ya books, but little "Little Altars" alone.</span>
  <a data-text-id="477599548004083294" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


